s is okay. Could I also use `xxd` on an existing compiled class? A few options are coming to mind.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Shortening class name**\\n\\nI realize I need a shorter class name for the generated bytecode. The class source I have is: \\n\\n```\\npackage com_google_inject.guice;\\npublic class BytecodeGenBridgeTarget {}\\n```\\n\\nI guess I can compile this with `javac` using the --release 8 option for compatibility. After that, I can use `xxd -i` to convert it to a byte array. Just need to check that everything aligns well! Let's get to it!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_BE9YAzVTl64SfyDAVp7W1E6y|fc_02c60363ed99b1c90169fa53a87488819f8d9c44735af1e6a5", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "tmpdir=$(mktemp -d); mkdir -p \"$tmpdir/com_google_inject/guice\"; printf 'package com_google_inject.guice; public class BytecodeGenBridgeTarget {}\\n' > \"$tmpdir/com_google_inject/guice/BytecodeGenBridgeTarget.java\"; javac --release 8 -d \"$tmpdir/classes\" \"$tmpdir/com_google_inject/guice/BytecodeGenBridgeTarget.java\"; xxd -i \"$tmpdir/classes/com_google_inject/guice/BytecodeGenBridgeTarget.class\"; rm -rf \"$tmpdir\"", "timeout": 30}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 4026, "output": 1434, "cacheRead": 19968, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 25428, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1778013071859, "responseId": "resp_02c60363ed99b1c90169fa539055f8819f83ec6f327cbee68e"}}
